title_narrative: 8. Mine Action and Cluster Munitions Programme 2016 -2020
sector_narrative: The RNG funded teams will be conducting a variety of clearance techniques to ensure maximum efficency. For the Battle area clearance of cluster munitions, HALO will use sub-surface clearance techniques combining the use of Large Loop metal detectors (LLDs) in open areas such as agricultural fields and Schoenstedt magnetic locators where the LLD can not work effectovely such as dense forest. When conducting clearance of minefields the teams will use the latest clearance techniques and technologies such as linear clearance with dual sesnor detectors (in Kosovo HALO uses HSTAMIDS).
description_narrative: HALO is funded to deliver a 48-month project in Kosovo with a total cost of $763,208 to clear minefields and NATO cluster munition strikes. $381,604 is being provided by the Dutch Government to conduct landmine and cluster munitions clearance. This will be matched by a private donor committed to providing matched funding to HALO for the clearance of all remaining minefields in the country.
It is proposed that the project will release the following land: - 3 NATO cluster munition strikes covering 160,000m², and 10 minefields covering 262,000m²

To achieve the outputs, the total project, including match funding, will employ 14 Kosovan national staff divided into two seven-person demining teams. Over four years, it is estimated that the project will support 191 direct and 3,323 indirect beneficiaries.

location_description_narrative: Many of the minefields left to clear are located on agricultural land and woodland in rural, remote areas of Kosovo. Landmines were laid extensively during the war in Kosovo in the late 1990s by former Yugoslav forces, which resulted in substantial contamination and thereby restricted access to agricultural land and woodlands.Towards the end of the Kosovo War, NATO bombed Yugoslav targets over a period of 78 days in 1999; hundreds of thousands of sub-munitions were dropped from cluster bombs during this campaign. Both American-made BLU-97s and British-made BLU-755s were dropped throughout Kosovo. An estimated 20% of all cluster munitions dropped failed to activate, leaving rural areas in the country littered with unexploded sub-munitions.

Beneficiary numbers are determined by task selection. Task selection was agreed after the submission of the 2019 annual plan. The beneficiary targets listed here were determined in 2020 with KMAC once tasks were selected.

As reported last quarter, the programme has revised the method it uses to calculate direct and indirect beneficiaries, resulting in higher direct beneficiaries number in general. However the particular BAC task which received clearance in 2020 by HALO is a public park in the centre of Peja city with thousands of direct beneficiaries. This task was not in HALO's original work plan for this project. However, due to Covid, the programme was restricted as to where teams could operate and the team directed clearance at this task because it remained accessible during this time.
